# #    Annotations
# #
# #################################################################
# 
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ActiveDevice> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "A device whose operation depends on a source of energy other than that generated by the human body or gravity." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ActiveDevice> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Active Device" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ActiveImplant> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "An active device intended to be totally or partially introduced into the human body and to remain there after the procedure." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ActiveImplant> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Active Implant" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ClassA> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Lowest risk class under IVDR (EU 2017/746). Devices pose minimal risk and include general laboratory instruments." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ClassA> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Class A" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ClassB> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Low-medium risk class under IVDR (EU 2017/746). Devices require limited notified body involvement." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ClassB> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Class B" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ClassC> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Medium-high risk class under IVDR (EU 2017/746). Devices require notified body intervention for conformity assessment." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ClassC> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Class C" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ClassD> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Highest risk class under IVDR (EU 2017/746). Devices pose the highest risk, such as tests for HIV or blood-group typing." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ClassD> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Class D" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ClassI> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Lowest risk class under MDR (EU 2017/745). Devices pose minimal risk to patients and users." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ClassI> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Class I" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ClassIII> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Highest risk class under MDR (EU 2017/745). Devices are subject to the most stringent conformity assessment, including clinical evaluation." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ClassIII> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Class III" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ClassIIa> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Medium-low risk class under MDR (EU 2017/745). Devices require involvement of a notified body for conformity assessment." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ClassIIa> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Class IIa" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ClassIIb> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Medium-high risk class under MDR (EU 2017/745). Devices require more stringent conformity assessment procedures." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ClassIIb> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Class IIb" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#Closed> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Status indicating that the field safety corrective action has been fully completed and verified." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#Closed> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Closed" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ContaminationRisk> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Risk of reagent or device contamination leading to systematic errors or patient harm." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ContaminationRisk> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Contamination Risk" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#Critical> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Severity level indicating a risk that could result in death or permanent serious injury." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#Critical> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Critical" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#CybersecurityRisk> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Risk arising from exploitable software vulnerabilities enabling unauthorised access or manipulation of device functions." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#CybersecurityRisk> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Cybersecurity Risk" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#DeviceFailure> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Risk category covering events where the device fails to perform its intended function due to electrical, mechanical or software issues." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#DeviceFailure> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Device Failure" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#DevicePerformance> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Risk category covering events related to suboptimal or unintended device performance without complete failure." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#DevicePerformance> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Device Performance" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#DeviceSafety> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Risk category covering events related to intrinsic safety hazards of the device, including cybersecurity threats." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#DeviceSafety> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Device Safety" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#DiagnosticError> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Risk category covering events where an in vitro diagnostic device produces incorrect results leading to misdiagnosis." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#DiagnosticError> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Diagnostic Error" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#DiagnosticRisk> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Risk of incorrect diagnostic output from an in vitro diagnostic device, including false positive or false negative results." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#DiagnosticRisk> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Diagnostic Risk" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#High> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Probability level indicating that the risk event is likely to occur under normal conditions of use." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#High> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "High" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#IVDR> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Regulation (EU) 2017/746 on in vitro diagnostic medical devices, classifying devices into classes A, B, C and D." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#IVDR> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "In Vitro Diagnostic Regulation" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ImplantableActiveDevice> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "A device that combines both active and implantable characteristics, requiring energy to \noperate while being implanted in the body." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ImplantableActiveDevice> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Implantable Active Device" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ImplantableDevice> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "A device intended to be totally or partially introduced into the human body and to remain there after the procedure, without depending on an energy source." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ImplantableDevice> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Implantable Device" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#InSituCorrection> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "A correction performed on a device at the location where it is installed or in use, without requiring its removal." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#InSituCorrection> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "In Situ Correction" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#InVitroDiagnosticDevice> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "A device intended for the examination of specimens derived from the human body to provide information on physiological or pathological conditions." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#InVitroDiagnosticDevice> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "In Vitro Diagnostic Device" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#InfectionRisk> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Risk of microbial contamination or device-related infection at the implantation site or systemically." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#InfectionRisk> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Infection Risk" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#InjuryRisk> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Risk of direct physical harm to a patient or user caused by the device." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#InjuryRisk> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Injury Risk" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#InterferenceRisk> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Risk of electromagnetic or physical interference affecting device performance or diagnostic imaging quality." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#InterferenceRisk> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Interference Risk" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#Low> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Probability level indicating that the risk event is unlikely to occur under normal conditions of use." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#Low> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Low" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#MDR> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Regulation (EU) 2017/745 on medical devices, classifying devices into classes I, IIa, IIb and III." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#MDR> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Medical Device Regulation" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#MalfunctionRisk> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Risk arising from the device failing to perform its intended function correctly." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#MalfunctionRisk> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Malfunction Risk" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#MaterialRisk> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Risk arising from adverse biological reactions to device materials, including wear debris or metallic ion release." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#MaterialRisk> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Material Risk" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#Medium> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Probability level indicating that the risk event may occur occasionally under normal conditions of use." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#Medium> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Medium" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#Moderate> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Severity level indicating a risk that could result in minor injury or temporary harm not requiring hospitalisation." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#Moderate> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Moderate" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#NearMissIncident> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "An incident where a malfunction occurred but did not lead to patient harm, though it had the potential to do so." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#NearMissIncident> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Near-Miss Incident" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#Open> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Status indicating that the field safety corrective action is currently active and not yet completed." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#Open> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Open" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#PatientHarm> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Risk category covering events that directly cause or may cause physical injury, infection or adverse reaction in a patient." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#PatientHarm> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Patient Harm" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ProductQuality> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Risk category covering events related to contamination, sterility failures or degradation of device components." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#ProductQuality> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Product Quality" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#RadiationRisk> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Risk of unintended ionising or non-ionising radiation exposure caused by the device." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#RadiationRisk> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Radiation Risk" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#Recall> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "An action to remove or correct a distributed device that presents a risk to health or does not conform to regulations." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#Recall> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Recall" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#SafetyAlert> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "A communication issued to healthcare professionals warning of a safety risk and providing updated instructions." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#SafetyAlert> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Safety Alert" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#SelfTestDevice> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "An in vitro diagnostic device intended to be used by lay persons in a home environment." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#SelfTestDevice> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Self-Test Device" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#Serious> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Severity level indicating a risk that could result in serious but reversible injury or hospitalisation." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#Serious> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Serious" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#SeriousIncident> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "An incident that directly or indirectly led to death, serious deterioration in health, or serious public health threat." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#SeriousIncident> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Serious Incident" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#SingleUseDevice> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "A device intended to be used on one individual during a single procedure and then discarded." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#SingleUseDevice> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Single-Use Device" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#SoftwareRisk> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "Risk arising from software defects causing incorrect device behaviour, dosing errors or alarm failures." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#SoftwareRisk> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "Software Risk" .
# 
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#UserNotice> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment> "A written communication sent to users providing updated instructions, warnings or procedural changes." .
<http://example.org/eudamed-ontology#UserNotice> <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#label> "User Notice" .
# 
